<BaseLayout title="How this archive works" description="The narrative-and-curation layer that sits alongside the structured family tree on FamilySearch. The tree is the index; this site is the book.">
  <article class="prose prose-stone max-w-prose">
    <h1>How this archive works</h1>
    <p class="text-ink/70 italic">
      The narrative-and-curation layer that sits alongside the
      structured family tree. The tree is the index; this site is the book.
    </p>

    <h2>The division of labor</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>The structured family tree lives on <a
      href="https://www.familysearch.org/tree/person/details/GMLW-PXW">FamilySearch</a></strong>
      &mdash; 3,428 individuals across 1,510 families as of June 2026, maintained
      by Chuck Eesley and Dale Eesley jointly, with the FamilySearch instance
      treated as canonical. The downloadable <a href="/docs/eesley-wildermuth-tree.ged">GEDCOM</a>
      and the <a href="/docs/dale-eesley-familysearch-tree/">tree-export page</a>
      are this site's mirrors of that record. A parallel Ancestry.com version of the
      tree exists too; the two are kept in rough sync but FamilySearch is the
      reference.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>This site is the narrative and curation layer that sits alongside
      the tree</strong> &mdash; the photographs and their captions, the documents
      transcribed in full, the essays that read across multiple people and
      places, and the family-memory layer that genealogy fields can't hold. The
      structured tree carries the names, the dates, the parents and the
      spouses. This site carries the rest.
    </p>

    <h2>What goes where</h2>
    <p>The split, in practice:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>FamilySearch</strong> &mdash; the structured record. Names,
        dates, parents, spouses, children, places of birth and death. The
        records-search engine and the collaborative-tree corrections layer that
        make the structured side function across many descendant lines. DNA
        matching where opted in.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>This site</strong> &mdash; the narrative record. Long-form
        biographical essays where they earn the length; photographs with
        labeled captions and provenance; documents transcribed in full
        (memoirs, letters, eulogies, obituaries) or curated by metadata
        (the <a href="/docs/letters-from-vietnam/">Letters from Vietnam</a>
        collection's policy is the canonical example); places with significance
        (a <a href="/places/highland-ridge-road-marietta/">single road in Lowell</a>
        carries a fuller account than its individual residents could); essays
        that cut across the structured tree (<a href="/docs/family-threads/">Family
        threads</a>, <a href="/docs/the-three-charleses/">the Three Charleses</a>,
        <a href="/docs/the-three-peggys/">the Three Peggys</a>, <a
        href="/docs/robert-earl-wildermuth-little-histories/">Robert Earl's
        Little Histories</a>); the family-memory layer that arrives by email
        from cousins (Roberta's June 2026 Aunt Ota stories are an instance);
        and the bilingual Chinese sections on every Zhou-side page.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Why two sites and not one</h2>
    <p>
      Both the structured-tree side and the narrative-curation side are doing
      real work, and trying to do both jobs in one platform makes both jobs
      worse. FamilySearch has the records-search engine, the millions of
      indexed vital records, the DNA-matching, and the collaborative tree
      &mdash; none of which would be feasible to rebuild here. This site has
      editorial control, full-document transcription, narrative-essay space,
      privacy policies the family can set rather than the platform, and
      &mdash; most importantly &mdash; <strong>file-level ownership of every
      piece of content</strong>. Static HTML, source code on
      <a href="https://github.com/charleseesley/family-chuckeesley-site">GitHub</a>,
      deployable to any web host or a USB drive. The longevity assurance is
      structural, not contractual.
    </p>
    <p>
      So the architecture is: the tree is the index; this site is the book.
      Each does what the other can't. Visitors who arrive at one side and
      want the other can find their way across via the links on the
      individual person pages.
    </p>

    <h2>The four content collections</h2>
    <p>The site's data model has four typed collections:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>People</strong> &mdash; one entry per person (family and
        non-family). Carry parents, spouses, dates, a one-paragraph summary
        in the frontmatter, then a Markdown body for the narrative. Cross-link
        bidirectionally to documents, places, and artifacts where they appear.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Documents</strong> &mdash; long-form narrative content. The
        type field distinguishes memoirs, combat logs, travelogues, registers,
        ancestor sketches, essays, letters, letter collections, eulogies,
        obituaries, and tree exports. Some are transcribed in full; some are
        catalogued by metadata only; the <a href="/docs/letters-from-vietnam/">Letters
        from Vietnam</a> collection page explains the curation principle.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Places</strong> &mdash; locations the family touched, with
        signatures and "then and now" pairings. The point of this collection is
        that some places were visited more than once across generations, and
        the resulting <a href="/places/rielingshausen-church/">multi-generation
        pilgrimage record</a> is itself an artifact about continuity.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Artifacts</strong> &mdash; catalogued objects, mostly
        photographs. Schema mirrors the field structure of Maggie Eesley's
        <em>Four Generations</em> archival catalog so her metadata imports
        nearly losslessly.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Editorial principles</h2>
    <p>A few principles run through the site and are worth naming explicitly:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Living people get a light touch.</strong> See the <a
        href="/about/privacy/">privacy page</a> for the full version.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Bilingual on every Zhou-side page.</strong> English at the
        top, full <span lang="zh">中文</span> below, on the same page. The
        practice of making the family record itself bilingual &mdash; rather
        than translating it later &mdash; is the data-model expression of the
        cross-cultural marriage the contemporary archive holds.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Curation policies are stated, not assumed.</strong> The Vietnam
        letters collection page says explicitly that a small published set is
        reproduced in full while the rest are catalogued by metadata only
        with the body held privately. Other policies (privacy, AI-generated
        imagery, family-memory sourcing) are stated where they apply.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Corrections are documented in place.</strong> When the date on
        a photograph is corrected (the c. 1979&ndash;85 Highland Ridge reunion
        portrait re-dated to c. 1971&ndash;72 per Roberta's June 2026 email),
        the prior reading and the correction trail stay on the page. The
        archive treats family memory as a primary source, and a primary
        source can be wrong; documenting the correction makes the editorial
        process visible.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Transmission chains are credited.</strong> Robert Earl's
        memoir → Chuck. Maggie's <em>Four Generations</em> deck →
        Chuck. Roberta's June 2026 email → this archive. The chain of
        family memory that brought each story here is the source line on
        every page.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The keepers</h2>
    <p>
      This archive is the next round in a long line of family record-keeping
      &mdash; from <a href="/family/mary-eesley-bean/">Mary Eesley Bean</a>'s
      1985 indented register, to <a href="/family/margaret-maggie-eesley/">Margaret "Maggie"
      Eesley</a>'s <em>Four Generations</em> photographic catalogue, to <a
      href="/family/robert-earl-wildermuth/">Robert Earl Wildermuth</a>'s
      1990 Wildermuth/Fleming Heritage and 1988&ndash;1993 memoir,
      to <a href="/family/dale-eesley-genealogist/">Dale Eesley</a>'s ongoing
      FamilySearch tree, to <a href="/family/roberta-burnes/">Roberta
      Burnes</a>'s curation of the paternal-side material into the next
      generation. The previous generations of keepers built the structured
      record. This site is the narrative layer Chuck is adding on top of it.
    </p>
    <p>
      Robert Earl closed his last manuscript by addressing
      <em>"future genealogists."</em> This site is one of them answering.
    </p>

